Analyzing Child HIV Prevalence Across Nine Different Countries of High HIV Prevalence¶

DATS 6103 - Fall 2020 - Jesse Liu¶

Project Purpose:¶

  • The purpose of the project is to analyze Child HIV prevalence data and compare it with that respective country's total healthcare spending per capita.

  • The countries chosen presented the highest HIV prevalence in their respective regions: Africa, Asia, and South America. The countries analyzed are: Nigeria, Kenya, Ethiopia, Mozambique, Myanmar, Haiti, Pakistan, Philippines, and Venezuela.

  • Children are defined as ages 0-14 years old in these analyzed datasets.

Presentation Outline:¶
  1. Importing Data
  2. Data Cleaning and Preprocessing
  3. Data Visualization and Analysis
  4. Conclusions

A) Overall Global Deaths in Children¶

In [59]:
#Creating Timeseries plot that compares total deaths from HIV in children ages 0-14 years old 
ad_global.plot(x='Year', y="Value", kind="bar", color = "green",  legend =False, figsize = (15,5))
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel("Estimated number of Annual AIDS-related Deaths", fontsize = 10)
plt.title("Global Estimated Number of Annual AIDS-related Deaths in Children vs. Years", fontsize = 15)
plt.grid(True)

B) Comparison of Children Living with HIV-AIDS¶

In [25]:
#Creating Timeseries plot that compares total children living with HIV AIDS
newannualrate_all.plot.line(y=["Nigeria", "Kenya", "Ethiopia", "Mozambique", "Venezuela", "Myanmar", "Haiti", "Pakistan", "Philippines"], figsize = (15,5))
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel("Total Estimated Number of Children", fontsize = 12)
plt.title("Total Estimated Number of Children Living with HIV-AIDS vs. Years", fontsize = 15)
plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
plt.grid(True)

Note: While total number of HIV deaths is decreasing, the total estimated number of children living with HIV-AIDS remains constant for most of the selected countries, with the exception of Kenya and Ethiopia.

In [48]:
#Creating Timeseries plot that compares total healthcare expenditure per capita (left axis) and annual new HIV infections (right axis)
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (15,5))
ax.plot(hc_tdata.index, hc_tdata.Nigeria, color="red", marker = "o")
ax.set_xlabel("Year", fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel("Healthcare Spending per Capita (USD)", color = "red", fontsize=14)
ax2 = ax.twinx()
ax2.plot(hc_tdata.index, newannual_all.Nigeria, color = "blue", marker = "o")
ax2.set_ylabel("Estimated number of Annual New HIV Infections", color="blue", fontsize=14)
ax.set_title('Nigeria: Healthcare Spending Per Capita and Estimated number of Annual New HIV Infections Vs. Year', pad=25, fontsize = 15)
plt.grid(True)

#Creating Timeseries plot that compares total healthcare expenditure per capita (left axis) and incidence of annual new HIV infections (right axis)
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (15,5))
ax.plot(hc_tdata.index, hc_tdata.Nigeria, color="red", marker = "o")
ax.set_xlabel("Year", fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel("Healthcare Spending per Capita (USD)", color = "red", fontsize=15)
ax2 = ax.twinx()
ax2.plot(hc_tdata.index, newannualinc_all.Nigeria, color = "green", marker = "o")
ax2.set_ylabel("Incidence Rate", color="green", fontsize=13)
ax.set_title('Nigeria: Comparison of Healthcare Spending Per Capita and New Incidence Rate Vs. Year', pad=25, fontsize = 15)
plt.grid(True)

Note: Catastrophic and impoverishing effects of out-of-pocket health payments (OOP) as a means of financing health system in Nigreia lead to increasing households incurring catastropic health payments and rise in poverty. : NIH (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6186489/).

National Health Act of 2014 proposed to expand social health insurance and guarantee universal health coverage for citizens by providing free health coverage. However, both Annual New HIV infections and incidence rates increased as a result.(https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4698843/)

Conclusions¶

  1. In 2014, the National Health Bill was enacted in Nigeria to enact social health insurance, which transitioned health payments from private out-of-pocket to a national system where health care was free for select citizens. This actually lead to an increase in annual new HIV cases and HIV incidence rate.

  2. Kenya, Ethiopia, Mozambique, and Myanmar show decreases in new HIV cases with increase in Healthcare Spending per capita.

  3. Pakistan shows an increase in healthcare spending per capita, but also an increase in new HIV cases in children. Pakistan has been criticized for insufficient healthcare protection for children.

  4. Venezuela's unique economic climate also presents a unique positive correlation between decrease in healthcare spending per capita and new HIV cases in children,.

  5. While Philippines has increased healthcare spending per capita, an HIV-AIDS epidemic currently requires a need to address this issue through policy changes in healthcare spending.

  6. Each HIV-AIDS situation is unique and it is important to provide the proper context from different regions (in terms of healthcare spending) in order to properly address the HIV-AIDS crisis that is of particular threat during this COVID-19 Pandemic.
